## The two trees (information model)

Everything the agent reads or writes lives in one of two trees, each with a distinct role. Keeping them separate is what prevents "source of truth" conflicts.

| Tree | Role | Holds | Written by |
|------|------|-------|-----------|
| `docs/` | **Deliverables** — the SDLC handover set | `01-brd/` → `10-demo-script/` (requirements, design, testing, demo) | specs-writer (02-04), system-design (05-08), planning (09-10) |
| `memory/` | **Agent state** | `active.md` (current task, next step), `decisions.md` (ADRs), `progress.md` (shipped features), `plan.md` (TASK-XXX) | planning, /memory, system-design, debug, migration (ADRs) |

Rule of thumb: `docs/` is the intent and the design; the **code** is the reality. If they ever disagree, the code is the tiebreaker — then update the matching deliverable to match.

The 10 deliverables: 01-BRD (you provide) · 02-SRS · 03-Use Cases · 04-Activity Diagrams · 05-Database Design · 06-Architecture · 07-API Design · 08-Frontend Design · 09-Testing · 10-Demo Script. Diagrams are **Mermaid** (inline). Every project keeps all 10 folders; non-applicable ones are marked **N/A**. See [docs/README.md](docs/README.md).

